The l-f-c-s exam, what to expect.

The linux foundation certified system administrator exam is a two-hour, online, performance-based test. There are no multiple-choice questions and no essays. Instead, you are given a real linux machine through your browser, you s-s-h into it, and you solve genuine tasks on a live system. It is purely do this, on this actual machine.

A few details are worth knowing, though you should always verify them on the official site before booking, as they do change. The exam runs for two hours. When you register, you choose your distribution, either an ubuntu long-term-support release or cent-o-s stream, and the exam machine matches your choice, so practise on the one you pick. The passing score has historically been around two-thirds. The format is roughly twenty to twenty-five hands-on tasks, each with a defined this-works criterion that is checked automatically. During the exam you may use the system's own documentation, the manual pages, the info system, and help flags, but no external websites and no offline notes. There is one free retake within twelve months if you do not pass, and the certification is valid for three years.

The exam is organised into domains, with rough weightings. Essential commands, the file and text work, is the largest at around a quarter. Operating running systems, including boot, services, and logs, is about a fifth. User and group management is around a tenth. Networking is about fifteen percent. Basic service configuration is around a tenth. And storage management, partitions, l-v-m, raid, mounts, swap, and quotas, is another fifth. Every one of these domains has been covered across the earlier notebooks, and this final one adds the scripting, troubleshooting, and cross-cutting pieces. The environment itself is a stripped-down machine into which you can install whatever packages you need, so do not be afraid to add tools as you go.
